The financial crisis had its roots in 1999 during the Clinton era, as the President was seeking a second term. He aimed to increase his popularity to extend his presidency. To achieve this, the Clinton administration relaxed lending restrictions, setting the grim stage for the subprime crisis seven years later. Steven Holmes of the New York Times reported in 1999, “Fannie Mae, the nation’s largest underwriter of home mortgages, has been under increasing pressure from the Clinton Administration to expand mortgage loans among low and moderate-income people and felt pressure from shareholders to maintain its phenomenal profit growth.” Holmes would later correctly predict the consequences of these actions: “But the government-subsidized corporation may run into trouble during an economic downturn, prompting a government bailout similar to that of the savings and loan industry in the 1980s.” As detailed in the introduction and as Holmes foresaw, ill-advised lending would certainly lead to the economy's collapse.

Several factors combined to send the economy into a tailspin, one of which was the new and complex structure of mortgages. Adjustable-rate mortgages, mortgage-backed securities, and collateralized debt obligations (CDOs) were extensively used in the years leading up to the crisis, only serving to intertwine more sectors of the economy with the housing market. This led U.S. households and financial markets in general to overleverage themselves in the housing market, leaving them extremely vulnerable to even small changes in price.

Indeed, the housing bubble burst, and the financial institutions that had purchased these mortgage-backed securities were hit hard. The top five U.S. investment banks collectively reported $4.1 trillion in mortgage debts in 2007, which accounted for about 30% of the USA's GDP. Ultimately, Bear Stearns and Merrill Lynch were sold exceptionally cheaply, Lehman Brothers was dismantled, and Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley were forced to become commercial banks subject to intense regulation. Fannie and Freddie were $5 trillion in mortgage debt and were placed under government control in September 2008.

Ah, exposition. That part of your story where you spread your little writer's wings and take off, amazing everyone with your magnetic, even magical prose. Or the part where your readers doze off and/or press the "Back" button while cursing your name. Dr. Merlin is known to yell at her monitor when she finds herself buried in too much information, and not even in a fun way.

Exposition is not your ally.

My gentle readers already know the basic writing advice, "Show, don't tell," yet Dr. Merlin still stumbles into lengthy passages where nothing occurs or, worse, too much. Exposition is that little devil on your shoulder telling you to get the backstory out of the way to reach the good parts (not to be confused with the devil on the other shoulder urging the author to tell the audience every single detail of each character's childhood).

Exposition means narrating to the audience what transpired, usually in straightforward prose. In film, exposition occurs when one character dumps a load of information onto another, akin to "The Rime of the Ancient Mariner." In fiction, it's the author doing the telling.

An example is fitting. As you read a story, you're informed the heroine met her beloved at a certain place and time, they married in a grand fashion, and her husband was murdered before her eyes. You wouldn't expect this whole sequence to span two pages, during which both he and she only get two lines of dialogue each. You'd anticipate the author spending time on the husband's character, illustrating through his speech and manner how deeply he loves his wife, and you'd likewise expect the heroine to show, in both big and small ways, how much his presence transformed and enriched her life (especially if the story later outright states this was the case). A proper introduction to the husband's character would allow you to become emotionally engaged with his fate and provide insights into the heroine's character: what she saw in him, the depth of their bond, clues about her thoughts, beliefs, and dreams as reflected through the prism of his eyes, and so forth. You would grieve his death with her, thus becoming more connected to the heroine herself.

In short, you'd expect substance on the simple storyline: "They met, they married, he died."

As a writer, you need to supply that substance. (*looks at metaphor, sighs, and continues*) Sometimes it's tempting to rush past certain details. Perhaps you're introducing a new character and you know he used to be in the Air Force, is now the night manager of a gas station, was married twice, has no kids, likes fishing on weekends, secretly dreams of owning the gas station someday, and had Eggs Benedict for breakfast.

I watched two news broadcasts from Columbus, Ohio. The first one, which was "live," was NBC 4 this morning (August 13, 2011). The main story was about a man in Ashley, Ohio, who had stabbed his wife. Her name wasn't mentioned, but his name was Shad Hostettler. They showed his mug shot, and he looked quite sinister. They only spent about two minutes on this story as it was still unfolding. The only details they provided were that he had stabbed her multiple times and had been arrested. I think they devoted an appropriate amount of time to this story.

The second story was about the early morning shooting of 18-year-old Travis Buyers. He was shot in the Sharon Woods area and was critically injured; there had been no arrests or suspects at the time. The SWAT Team was investigating the crime. This story seemed brief, and I think it might have been because he was a "black" man or it happened in a black neighborhood. I have noticed (for years now) that minorities are often overlooked when they are victims of crime. If a "white" child or adult is kidnapped, missing, or a victim of a crime, the media goes wild; but if it's a minority person, it's lucky if it even gets mentioned.

The next story was about a bullet hole found in the Med-Flight helicopter. Details were provided about where they thought the incident occurred. It was determined that a .22 caliber bullet from a rifle had hit the helicopter. Crime-Stoppers are offering a five-thousand dollar reward for tips that lead to the arrest of the shooter.

The next story was about the rain and thunderstorms predicted for Saturday afternoon. They said temperatures would remain in the mid to low eighties for the weekend. The segment was a bit short, but they wanted to use it as a "teaser" to keep viewers tuned in.

They also covered a story about a robbery at a Clime Road UDF in Columbus. They said a dark-skinned black man robbed the store and he was wearing a hoodie sweatshirt. He was described as about six feet tall and weighing around one hundred and fifty pounds. I thought they spent an unusual amount of time emphasizing that he was black and how dark his skin was.

Another story was about Rene Rodriguez, a convicted Texas drug kingpin. He was convicted of conspiring to distribute large amounts of marijuana to Ohio from Texas. One curious thing I noted was that instead of saying he was sentenced to twenty-five years in prison, they said "300" months. I'm not sure what the purpose was there, whether they thought it sounded harsher or something else. They also mentioned he was Hispanic, which I don't think was really relevant to the story.

An ETF, or exchange-traded fund, is a security designed to track an index, a commodity, or a basket of assets like an index fund but offers more flexibility and trades like a stock on an exchange. An ETF provides the diversification of an index fund and the benefits of individual stock ownership, such as the ability to short sell, buy on margin, and purchase as few as one share in any transaction. Although these benefits are highly attractive, the expense ratios of ETFs are much lower than those of the average mutual fund. Unfortunately, there are some downsides, such as the need to pay a commission on any trade involving ETFs, just as you would on a stock order. Another advantage of ETFs is the wide variety of funds available. While these benefits are clearly stated, it is always a good practice for the savvy financial investor to verify whether stated benefits, like diversification, indeed exist and to what extent they are present. For this purpose, we will examine the ETF IHF and compare it to the top 10 holdings that make up the ETF to determine whether the benefits of owning a single ETF come close to owning a diversified portfolio of the ten stocks and whether better configurations of the same stocks exist that would provide a more optimal Sharpe ratio or return.

To evaluate the ETF, including every holding would be rather unwieldy, so we have decided to include only the top ten holdings accounting for 63.58% of all the assets in the ETF. Below are the top 10 holdings and the percentage of total assets.

To estimate how well these ten stocks represent the ETF IHF as a whole, we can use the current percentage of assets, normalized to 100%, to calculate the contributions of each stock to a portfolio's Beta and return if the portfolio consisted entirely of these 10 stocks in the proportion established by the ETF through their holdings. The calculations of Beta and return are included in the chart below.

From the above chart, it is evident that the return of a portfolio containing only the top 10 holdings is 6.11% higher than the ETF, a 16% increase in returns. It is also evident that the Beta of the top ten holdings is 0.12 lower than the ETF as a whole. From the results completed thus far, it seems that a portfolio of just the top 10 holdings could provide a higher return with a lower beta. However, there is a possibility that the means of these two portfolios may not be statistically different from each other.

To evaluate whether these portfolios are statistically different, the standard deviation of each of the top 10 stocks is determined and normalized to 100% to compare their accumulated standard deviation to that of the ETF IHF.

Referring to Figure 17, there was a sharp decline in commuter log submissions in the third month of the project. This was somewhat discouraging, and it is difficult to determine the cause. With the onset of winter on a New England campus, there is clearly a decrease in people commuting by bicycle or on foot, which might explain part of the decline. December also marks the end of the fall semester when everyone is busy finishing schoolwork, processing grades, and so on. For many, filling out the commuter log might have simply slipped off the radar. Additionally, December brings the busy holiday season and a month-long break for students and faculty, during which many do not need to come to campus at all. Classes resume for the spring semester in late January, which might also provide a clue to the low number of logs for that month. However, none of this really explains the low number of submissions in February. It could also be speculated that such projects tend to have an initial burst of energy and enthusiasm that might naturally wane. To counter this trend, we launched the Carpool Challenge Week, a special blitz campaign in March to reinvigorate the initiative, resulting in an increase in log submissions for that month. Thus, one of the challenges we faced was maintaining project momentum in the face of both a natural decline in engagement and specifically the problem of holiday and semester breaks in higher education. Another challenge for this project (or any alternative commuting project) is the simple fact that people enjoy the freedom, independence, and flexibility of driving their cars. This is deeply rooted in our culture. Therefore, it is essential to provide incentives for engaging in alternative commuting methods. We distributed many prizes in the form of gift certificates to local restaurants, coffee shops, massage therapists, the local independent bookstore, and even some larger national chain stores. However, it would have been interesting to see how some even larger prizes might have affected participation—such as giving away a nice bicycle, hybrid car, or electric car. This could have also helped combat the decline in engagement experienced by the project. The nature of the prizes did not really change during the course of the project. However, if the prizes had increased in value over the course of the project, that might have helped. The gift cards seemed more than adequate at the start of the project, but if we had announced the addition of a couple of bicycles in December, and then a hybrid or electric car in January, one can only speculate that participation and engagement would have increased rather than decreased.

While exploring the Library of Congress's collection of early Edison films, I chose to watch all the trick films, which numbered fifteen from 1895 to 1901. These films typically use creative editing to create illusions. My film study mainly focused on describing the poetics of most trick films and examining the evolutionary unique features found in some of the later films. Generally, the trick film at the turn of the century is stage-bound, composed within a frontal proscenium, shows no camera movement, uses long and medium shots, and adheres to the strict one shot = one film method. However, there are some films at the beginning of the twentieth century that dare to break these rules by introducing elements like multiple shots.

One of the most noticeable features that trick films share is their shooting in an interior setting within the frame of a frontal proscenium. The camera does not move from its proscenium position to follow figures or objects. This composition was very common in early films and has its roots in theater, and for trick films, in vaudeville and magic acts. One limitation inherent in using the stage is that figures in trick films generally only move side-to-side and do not walk toward or away from the camera. Consider, for example, the action in the film Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel (1900). The actors enter from the right side and move back and forth along the horizontal axis. Even when they go out of the frame, the camera does not follow them.

The frontal proscenium style of composition also means that shots tend to be long shots and, more rarely, medium shots. Close-ups are never used in any of the trick films from the Edison catalog. This is borrowed from theater and vaudeville tradition, where the audience would see the entire performance at any given time, framed by the stage's borders. As in most early films, the actors do not move from the middle ground towards the camera, so close-ups never occur.

Generally, most early trick films follow the pattern that one conceptual shot equals a film. This limits the length of most trick films to about a minute or less, depending on the frames per second used. It also limits the dramatic or narrative use of the trick films; most focus on short vaudeville-style tricks, such as magic, disappearing, and switching acts with little story. However, note that in a trick film, one conceptual shot in the viewer's eyes does not actually equal one physical shot. A single "shot" may actually consist of several joined together to create the illusion of appearing or disappearing. Look closely at The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots (1895), one of the earlier trick films. A more thorough inspection reveals the moment where the physical shot with Mary's severed "head" begins, even though the entire film is conceptually one shot to the viewer.

The traditional "Gothic Novel" is essentially an "oxymoron for 'Old-New,'" as Ian Watt describes in The Rise of the Gothic Novel. The Gothic style has received both criticism and praise, accused of lacking real depth and celebrated for its 'terrible sublime' quality (Burke). The original "Gothic Novel," Horace Walpole's The Castle of Otranto, combined "ancient and modern" romance ideas to create the proto-Gothic genre and a new form of literary expression. Walpole uses "old" theatrical elements and 'new' mimicry of nature in 'modern' novels to present what he calls "A Gothic Story" (Walpole 4). The Gothic genre borrows many elements from medieval gothic theater, architecture, and traditions. Even at the time of The Castle of Otranto's publication, "gothic" described various peoples, styles, and eras. It was considered archaic or unsophisticated compared to "modern" societal and literary "advancements." The mix of the theatrical "Gothic" and the novel's new format (offering readers personal insight into characters' psychology) allows Gothic to persist for such a long time, becoming simultaneously outdated and new to readers distanced in time from the original work.

A prominent gothic concept in Gothic novels is Chivalry. The medieval idea of chivalry, the training of a proper knight, is both preserved and transformed in the original Gothic novel, The Castle of Otranto. Chivalry is significant to Gothic writers for what it represented—the classic knight, brave, honorable, competent—and the perceived lack of that ideal, noted by writers (particularly Walpole) in society. Through chivalric concepts and manners, the "gothic past" is idealized and romanticized (suggesting Gothic's evolution to Romantic) to attempt to improve the present. While writing The Castle of Otranto, Walpole was in a politically troubled time, despairing over the future. Immersed in politics and (arguably) unfair accusations, he may have thought, even if not explicitly, that the supposed morality and innate "goodness" of people in the gothic era had somehow been lost in 'present' society. This idea is evident in his writing through characters like Frederic. Before meeting Frederic, readers see he embodies many chivalric traits, as described:

His description includes many traditionally chivalric images; Frederic is primarily a prince, he has suffered, been shaped by tragedy, and is believed to have been killed by infidels. The "gallant and courteous Knight" figure is exaggerated, bringing in the Gothic trope of excess (66).

Supply chain management encompasses the flow of processes to move goods from the customer order through raw materials, supply, production, and distribution to the customer. The term was coined in 1982 by consultant Keith Oliver, who detailed the overall process of planning, implementing, and controlling the supply chain to meet customer needs efficiently. There are six key elements: production, supply, inventory, location, transportation, and information, which managers use to deliver excellent customer service.

Production is the first step and forms the foundation of the supply chain process. It determines when, why, where, and how everything is produced. Managers need insight into customer desires, often gleaned from observing the market. After analyzing market demand, they decide which products to produce and in what quantities. Once these decisions are made, they determine the best location for production that meets volume and quality demands, ensuring customer satisfaction. The subsequent focus is on scheduling workloads and maintaining equipment. Attention to detail is crucial, as poor planning can cost time and money. For instance, both Wal-Mart and Target have structured processes for every aspect of business, from employee uniforms to receiving shipments, ensuring smooth operations.

The second key element is supply, involving strategic decisions about a facility's core capabilities and potential outsourcing partnerships. A company might have several production divisions for a single product, each with unique equipment, workers, and expertise. The manager must choose the best division for each process or consider outsourcing to enhance speed. Speed refers to the ability to maintain quality and flexibility while reducing or maintaining low costs.

Victorian novels are known for their meticulous attention to detail and their focus on the aristocracy of the time. Two novels that are considered Victorian but deviate from this tradition are "Oliver Twist" and "Wuthering Heights." Both novels incorporate an element of mystery and a penchant for the bizarre, uncommon for novels of the period, which enhances the characters within each work by providing insights into their motives and emotions.

"And now, throngs of bewildering and confusing thoughts crowded his mind. He seemed to still be walking between Sikes and Crackit, who were angrily disputing: for the very words they said echoed in his ears; and when he caught his own attention, ... he found he was talking to them... Suddenly he recoiled at the sound of firearms; and loud cries and shouts rose into the air; lights flickered before his eyes, and everything was noise and tumult, as some unseen hand hurriedly bore him away. Through all these rapid visions, there ran an undefined, uneasy consciousness of pain, which wearied and tormented him incessantly." (Dickens, 220)

The two novels often utilize this mystery through dream sequences or dreamlike states, though the content and function vary in each specific case. In "Oliver Twist," these strange occurrences often reveal insights into Oliver's inner layers, what pains him, and his awareness of the true nature of the things happening around him. When the shooting of Oliver is revisited in chapter 28, he vividly relives the shooting as if in a dream while struggling to find help. The passage emphasizes the lack of control Oliver had over the events that unfolded, as well as the dire condition of his health, which was strongly present through Oliver's hallucinations of Sikes and Crackit. The shooting itself overwhelms him, all his senses are numbed as he does not notice the "unseen hand" that carries him away; he experiences his despair again, removed from the shock of pain, as the pain is now constant and linked with fear rather than surprise. With Oliver being overwhelmed, the question arises about whose will brought about his misfortune, as it was certainly not his own. This shooting reinforces the idea that Oliver has little control over anything, as he cannot even bring himself to attempt to gain control of an event's outcome, even when his life is in danger. A growing sense of defeat in Oliver is also implied by this passage, as if old Fagin had begun to break him, forcing him to accept this despair, affecting his ability to react. Otherwise, it can be assumed that Oliver would have made some effort, at least simply for the sake of his own life.

"The day passed off – day! There was no day; it was gone as soon as it came – and night came on again; night so long, and yet so short; long in its dreadful silence and short in its fleeting hours.

A few years ago, I tutored elementary students in an after-school program. I tried my best to assist them in subjects where they struggled, though my strengths were in English and reading. One of the instructors asked for my help with a boy named Adrian (I think he was in third or fourth grade), who had significant reading difficulties. I realized something was amiss; he had unusual problems. Some letters he could pronounce perfectly, others not at all, which was quite odd. He was of Latino descent, I was certain of that, but the boy spoke flawless English. We continued to struggle until I met his mother one day. I was supervising a few children (for lack of a better word) while the rest of the group was on a field trip when his mother came in. She spoke no English, only Spanish. With my very limited Spanish (I was just learning), we managed to communicate. Then it hit me like a bolt: Adrian could read well, he just wasn't very familiar with the English alphabet. I don't know if this insight ever helped him much, but I hope he's doing better now.

I share this story to highlight the issue of language barriers in schools, particularly in California. It also illustrates that it's not always as clear as we might assume. Even a child who speaks perfect English can find reading a significant challenge. I think everyone agrees this problem exists, so what should we do? In Adrian's case, the solution was relatively straightforward: tutoring in English reading, focusing on the alphabet and pronunciation. But for many children who barely speak English, the solution is much more complex. There's no single answer. The dual language system, mainstream immersion, private tutors, ESL classes—none of these alone will solve the problem. The key is in combining all of these!

First and foremost, the dual language system is an excellent idea. Not just for children whose first language is Spanish, but for all children. "Children in two-way bilingual education programs tend to outperform their peers academically." There is a lot of fear around this idea, believing it's a waste of resources and that most children won't benefit. But that's not true. If we implemented these programs as a standard in classrooms, rather than an exception, all children would benefit. How do we implement this? Do we require all teachers to be bilingual? No, that would be unreasonable and somewhat unrealistic. However, I do believe there's no reason we can't have special aides, tutors, or whatever you want to call them, who are bilingual.

From the time we are children, most of us are told there is something out there larger than we are, beyond our comprehension. Some are sent to Sunday school to learn about it, others go to the temple, or seek answers within themselves. Many of us readily accept the religions passed down by our parents. Yet, some of us reject them entirely, denying that anything exists beyond our own personal egocentric universe. We might embrace one set of values only to change our minds later and adopt another. Whatever path we choose, we embark on a journey to define a part of ourselves through our personal views of spirituality. We search for a light in the darkness to lead us out of the shadows into the sun.

"A cardinal," my father said when I asked him his favorite bird. We sat on our house's porch, listening to the rain pounding on the tin roof above us while we smoked our cigarettes together. The gutters channeled the rain, drowning the plants along the porch's edge. He looked out into the rain, his gaze a mix of searching and remembering. He had grown thinner over the past months, his clothes hanging loosely from his body. His hair was sparser than I remembered. He kept staring into the rain, avoiding eye contact. I felt alone, afraid, and unable to talk to my father about how much I would miss him because discussing it would only make it more real for both of us. I hugged him, sat back down, moved my chair a little closer to his, and joined him in looking out into the falling rain of the June twilight.

My father passed away in December that year, five days after my twenty-second birthday. The chemo and radiation hadn't eased his suffering but kept him alive a few more months beyond the doctors' predictions; what value there was in merely prolonging his suffering, I could not define. What kind of God would allow this, I wondered. Alone at night, I offered no prayers. If God existed, I thought, he had stopped listening to me long ago.

I hadn't wanted to watch him transition from this life to another. So I didn't. I couldn't bear to watch the life that created me as it ended. I wanted to remember my father by how he lived, not how he died. Besides, I knew my father better than they did, better than his family, and knew Dad wouldn't want his only child to witness his passing. I curled up in a ball in my bed for three days and waited for the news.

No one even called me.

John Taylor of Caroline was an early and passionate advocate of Republicanism. Although he was primarily an agriculturist, this very profession, along with his brief political career, made him known for his commitment and outspokenness on matters of personal freedom and government. His dedication to an agrarian system was the foundation for nearly all his views on government. It was his attempt to preserve and promote what he considered the most superior of all careers that shaped his arguments on sovereignty, constitutionality, and even the judicial system.

John Taylor believed that the United States had a great opportunity to create an ideal system because there was no native tradition to hinder the creators of the government, allowing for the establishment of a system of self-government. He strongly believed in the natural rights of man and that they are all interdependent—meaning that if one is denied, they all will fail, and the value of those remaining is diminished. These rights should therefore be beyond the reach of the government. He claimed that what some called the "state of nature" meant that those with physical strength and malevolent intelligence were the ones that profited, but that this must not be the case in a civilization.

To create this ideal society, Taylor believed that a government must be created that accounts for the inherent good and evil in man. Taylor was very strict in his views on dualistic morality. He claimed that "as government is exercised by man, all its virtues and vices must be human" (Ibid., pg. 167). He defined good principles as those that protect private property, improve agriculture, and discourage capitalism, and believed that a government founded on good principles would function fairly regardless of its administration, which would inevitably be led by greed and self-interest. He believed self-interest was man's motivation in all things, but that the trait was only deemed evil when it extended beyond the creation of a society based on public good to sub-societies living at the expense of others. A good government was necessary to contain man's natural evil, and even then it must be under careful observation to avoid the addition of bad principles.

Taylor, like many other staunch Republicans of his time, called for a strict construction of the Constitution. He wanted an extremely limited Federal government, with no more rights or powers granted to it than were explicitly stated in the Constitution. He knew that an extensive Federal government was expensive and therefore likely to be despotic. However, he believed that a simple, literal interpretation was dangerous and that without reference to the intent of the writers, such a method could easily become corrupt. Furthermore, he considered the Declaration of Independence the true charter of the United States, because it more explicitly describes the country as a group of sovereign states rather than one nation.

Downwards I stared, my mind blankly taking in the view before me. Unemotionally and silently, with a practiced awareness that studied but refused to connect the object to any abstract understanding, my mind analyzed the picture before my eyes. Thoughts slipped in and out of my mind almost faster than they appeared. My consciousness worked so smoothly and cleanly that it seemed I had no real thoughts of my own, just an active and fluid experience of what I was observing. Once, following advice from an artist I worked with, I purchased an art instruction book called The New Drawing on the Right Side of the Brain. I had wanted to learn how to draw since I was six years old, and this book teaches everything from understanding what a pencil is to the brain processes used to interpret lines. One technique the book teaches is to place a square frame around any picture the artist wants to study. This transforms an overwhelmingly detailed picture, like a bowl of fruit on a table in a kitchen connected to a dining room, into an easily grasped image, that bowl of fruit on a simple plane. At that moment, staring down at the bowl before me, I couldn't mentally project that artist’s frame. I was so overwhelmed, so in awe that I could only stand and gaze in wonder. Picasso had his blue phase, Monet loved greenery, and Italian Renaissance masters displayed a rainbow of colors. If I had any pretensions of casting my perspective as worthy of the title Artistic, then before me were the beginnings of my picture, the start of my story, Work in Brown. Fingertips touched my chosen tool of artistry, muscles tightened and relaxed as my hand moved through space, my mind’s will given shape and form in what could have been the most creative moment of my life. Water swirled, serene and smooth, crystal clear and clean. Flakes of matter broke away from the whole and were carried away to nothingness. Muscles tightening, jerking, and spasming a bit more quickly and anxiously the second time, my hand hit the toilet handle again. The offensive brown package refused to move, stuck like a slug at the bottom of the toilet. Mop gripped loosely in hand, feet set a foot apart, green tie knotted uncomfortably around my throat, I frowned slightly as I stared at the rude bundle of processed animal and plant matter someone had left as a message for those unfortunate enough to clean the bathrooms at Rite Aid. A few more flushes, a few more tranquil introspective moments to myself, then my hand moved towards the wall to my right, grabbed the sheet at the end of the toilet paper, and began wrapping itself until it resembled an oven mitt. Standing up straight, then bending at the waist, my hand dipped slowly into the bowl, like a mother retrieving the Thanksgiving turkey from an oven.

Teenagers are dying behind the wheel. Several factors combine to create this deadly statistical trend for the youngest American drivers. The National Institutes of Health point out that part of the problem is that the teenage brain is literally not prepared for the dangers of driving. Simple inexperience is also at the heart of the issue. This inexperience not only leads to more fatal accidents but also results in higher rates of vehicle rollovers, speeding, and driving off the road. Teens also perform much worse when traveling with their peers, which is something anyone with common sense knows they do regularly. The Southern California Injury Prevention Research Center conducted a study showing a correlation between the age of passengers and the number of traffic accidents. California and other states have tried to improve teen driver safety by requiring temporary provisional licenses that limit the hours teens can drive and prohibit other minors as passengers. However, in my opinion, provisional licenses are merely temporary solutions. The real problem is that, as a group, the youngest drivers are simply not able to adequately handle the risks and responsibilities, as all statistical indicators show. Psychologist Marvin Zuckerman believes that even 18 is too young for a regular driver's license. USA Today reports that Zuckerman's research suggests that those under 19-20 years of age have a common desire to take risks for the thrill of it. Therefore, it makes sense to delay driving until the thrill-seeking tendency begins to subside. If we continue to issue driver's licenses to young teens, we will not only keep seeing deadly accidents, but the death toll is likely to reach alarming levels in the coming years. By 2010, the children of the Baby Boomers will be eligible to drive, and millions of new teen drivers will be ready to take to the road. Legislation on this issue would be relatively straightforward. Schools could continue to offer driver's education classes to start the learning process for future drivers, but no one under 18 would be allowed to operate a motor vehicle. A provisional permit could still be issued before granting a full driver's license, and a certain number of practical driving hours would be required. The specific number of hours could be based on those already required by most states (in California, for example, it is currently 6 hours of behind-the-wheel training and 50 hours of practice with an adult). Since the deadly statistics for teen drivers come from a cross-section of all states, uniform national legislation on this issue would be a reasonable—and I believe effective—way to protect teens across the country. The legislation I propose is by no means a novel idea.

This article explores three aspects of Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD). It begins with a brief definition of the disorder. Then, it explains the diagnosis process, highlighting typical characteristics or "red flags." Finally, the article discusses how a teacher in an inclusive classroom can support a student with CAPD.

Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD), also known as Auditory Processing Disorder (APD), refers to how efficiently and effectively the central nervous system (CNS) processes auditory information. It is narrowly defined as the perceptual processing of auditory information in the CNS and the neurobiological activity that underpins this processing and leads to electrophysiological auditory potentials (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). In other words, it is a disorder where the central nervous system (i.e., the brain) struggles to process what is heard correctly. People with CAPD can hear normally, so they are not classified as "hearing impaired"; rather, the brain area responsible for interpreting what is heard, such as distinguishing words or separating conversation from background noise, does not function as it typically should.

The earliest mention of the disorder, which evolved into CAPD, dates back to the mid-1950s, then known as "auditory imperception" (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005) when researchers evaluated children with communication disorders. The Italian research team of Bocca, Calearo, and Cassinari began developing tests for these children in 1954. In 1961, Kimura introduced dichotic testing and formulated a model to explain the physiology of the CANS underlying dichotic perception (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). A national conference in 1977 sparked research on children with CAPD.

CAPD manifests in various ways: the affected person may struggle to localize or hear where a sound is coming from; may find it difficult to distinguish between two or more "acoustic events" (sound occurrences); may not recognize sound patterns; may not perceive changes in speech (like detecting sarcasm through tone changes); one sound may be blocked by a subsequent sound; may lack the ability to synthesize sound cues (i.e., interpret them meaningfully to act upon them); and may not determine the sequence in which auditory information is presented (Ferre).

To diagnose CAPD, the patient must undergo a "systematic observation of listening behavior and/or performance on tests of auditory function," conducted by "audiologists, SLPs, psychologists, and others using a variety of measures to assess auditory-related skills" (American Speech-Language-Hearing Association, 2005). This may include questionnaires and surveys, observation of auditory behaviors, and responses to specific stimuli. Currently, no single tool or test is consistently used with a high diagnostic success rate, and the disorder's cause is unknown. Many tests present patients with multiple simultaneous auditory stimuli and ask them to differentiate specific items, such as a series of words or numbers. More advanced tests involve recording acoustic signals within the ear and measuring responses to these signals.

In pursuing an education in social work, I aim to build a career with the Division of Family and Children Services to assist children who have been abused or neglected and to support families in distress. Values I bring to the field include service, respect, ethical conduct, dedication to improving relationships between others, and my own professional development to remain competent in my field. These core values are not only crucial for social workers; they are personally significant to me.

I have always had the desire to help others, but I was unsure of which career path to follow. During my high school and college years, I witnessed many people deny their problems and a few resorted to less ideal coping mechanisms. Due to these experiences, I chose to pursue a Bachelor's degree in Psychology. Still uncertain about a career path, I decided to take a break after graduating from Piedmont College in 2009. One summer day, I visited a friend who introduced me to a sixteen-year-old boy sitting nervously on her couch. She explained he was there to escape his abusive parents. The following day, I learned he had called the police to his parents’ home. To see if I could help, I drove to his parents' house. Once there, I privately shared my concerns with the police and mentioned that I had just graduated with a degree in Psychology from Piedmont College. The police asked me to speak with the parents since the law could do nothing for the teenager. When I questioned the parents about the situation, they appeared nervous and made excuses, describing their son's "manipulative" behavior in seeking outside help for "simple" disputes. After this particular experience, I seriously considered a career in social work to help children with "simple" family disputes.

Another important value for the field of social work is social justice. As a society, we claim to value the individual and mourn those we lose. However, the concept of the "individual" upheld by society is more of a follower of archaic traditions than true uniqueness. If society mourns lost individuals, why do we strive to be like "everyone else"? I am an individual and I do not enjoy limiting myself to be similar to others. Throughout high school and college, I protested against social injustice whenever I could: by dyeing my hair unnatural colors, wearing clothes that matched my personality, piercing my ears beyond the traditional set, declaring my involvement with the GSBA (Gay Straight Bisexual Alliance), and fighting against racism and discrimination whenever I witnessed it. I believe in social justice and will continue to protest against social injustice.

The subsequent paper discusses the Biological and Sociocultural models concerning the disorder of insomnia. The biological model focuses on inherited genetic information and medical aspects of health. The sociocultural models examine environmental relationships and their application to race, ethnicity, demographics, and socioeconomic status. This review of insomnia analyzes these models, explaining each piece of research selected to relate to and better clarify the models. The research explanations and their findings are then critically assessed to highlight their specific strengths and weaknesses.

A sleep disorder can be defined as a primary sleep disorder, a sleep disorder related to another mental disorder, or a sleep disorder associated with other issues. Primary sleep disorders are Dyssomnias or Parasomnias, while those related to another mental disorder are linked to Axis I or Axis II disorders. Other categories of sleep disorders may arise from medical complications or substance intake. Dyssomnias include: Primary Insomnia, Primary Hypersomnia, Narcolepsy, Breathing-Related Sleep Disorder, Circadian Rhythm Sleep Disorder, and Dyssomnia Not Otherwise Specified (NOS). While Primary Insomnia involves complications in initiating or maintaining sleep, Primary Hypersomnia is characterized by difficulties in staying awake, both persisting for at least one month. Narcolepsy involves cataplexy and/or automatic REM. While Dyssomnias focus on falling and staying asleep, Parasomnias are sleep disorders linked to behavioral abnormalities and/or physiological occurrences. Parasomnias include Nightmare Disorder, Sleep Terror Disorder, Sleepwalking Disorder, and Parasomnias Not Otherwise Specified. Sleep disorders related to another mental disorder encompass sleep difficulties due to Axis I (Clinical Disorders) or Axis II (Personality Disorders or Mental Retardation). This review focuses on insomnia and somewhat on primary sleep disorders in general, in relation to the biological and sociocultural models.

The biological model of sleep disorders emphasizes genes, hereditary factors, and physiologically acquired aspects of sleep disorders. Neurons in the hypothalamus containing orexin are responsible for regulating sleep and wakefulness. This study experimented with mice and discovered phenotypic GABAB receptors on orexin neurons specifically responsible for sleep/wake states. Activation of the GABAA receptor induces responses that promote sleep. If its firing is inhibited, it can reduce anxiety and promote sleep. The GABAB agonist (baclofen) increased sleep time (Matsuki et al., 2009). Such results suggest that the animal models of mice can be generalized to human studies. This indicates that there is a genetic and environmental basis for the physical GABAB receptor in humans. A problem or absence with this receptor could impair one's ability to sleep adequately without medication. The sociocultural implication of this study is that if the phenotype is inherited, it could regulate sleep, and an alteration of the receptor would naturally disturb an individual's sleep. This would negatively affect aspects of life such as education, career, and daily events that require monotonous tasks and focus.

I have been studying at University Park for about two and a half years, or four and a half semesters. For many of us, including myself, navigating the campus can be tough. During my freshman year, I lived in a dorm room in East Halls, which is practically the furthest point east on campus, not counting the stadium and Bryce Jordan Center. It could take up to 25 minutes to walk from my home in Stuart Hall to classes in far-off locations like the Willard building near the campus center, especially when the weather was bad, which it often is in State College. An alum just a bit older than me told me that not long ago, East Halls dorms were separated from the rest of the campus by large areas of unused land. Today, that space has been filled with sports fields, large new buildings like the new Creamery and health services building, and surrounded by apartments. As our campus keeps expanding, moving from place to place becomes more challenging. What’s the best solution to this mobility issue? On a college campus, it’s the bicycle. But a bike alone won’t solve anything. Students need to ride them, and the campus must be designed to meet cyclists’ needs.

I was talking with a friend who recently got back into biking after a few years of not riding. He mentioned that he wondered why he ever stopped. “Bikes are awesome,” he said, “for a while it wasn’t cool to ride, but it’s the only way to get around.” Besides being good for your health, biking is the most efficient way to travel. A bowl of oatmeal and a bit of physical effort can take you 30 miles or more. Like many undergraduates, I now live off campus, just as far from the campus center as some dorms. The smartest choice I made this year was buying a bike. Every day, I have classes in the Thomas building, which is easily a twenty-five-minute walk from my home. Riding a bike can cut that time down to 5 minutes if I pedal quickly. The only problem is, Pollock Road is the most direct route to Thomas from my house, and it’s not always easy to travel on, whether by bike or not. There are benefits to walking too, but I’m too busy to walk. Without my bike, walking would be my only dependable way to get to class. Walking to Thomas every day would take an additional 30-40 minutes out of my day. That’s over two and a half hours each week. Add to that the time I’d spend walking to other classes, appointments, etc. That’s more time than I can spare.

Aldous Huxley, in his novel "Brave New World," critiques the looming threat of technology and the capitalist structure that is reinforced through the creation of a dystopia. The inhabitants of this world prioritize community over the individual and are conditioned from the start to seek immediate happiness above all else. The citizens are revealed to be pawns in a larger scheme, confined to a single ideology dictated by the World Controller. When the work is examined through the lens of Marxist theism, the author’s underlying concerns about the development of these systems become apparent. Frequent Marxist terms like homogeneity and reification emphasize that Huxley’s novel comments on the flaws of the emerging economy of his time.

Capitalism is satirized using the Marxist thesis of false consciousness. Essentially, the common citizenry is prevented from understanding their true economic relations with other classes, as they are primarily focused on their own gain. This is seen as a result of ideological control over the proletariat and common laborers, something made obvious through the conditioning in "Brave New World." The common classes, Delta, Gamma, etc., lack true will; through hypnopaedia, the impulse to consume, spend, and indulge is elevated above everything else. This is manipulated by the World Controller, as previously stated. Hegemony, essentially the idea that social classes are completely dominated by a separate group of individuals, is clearly employed in this scenario. The lower classes are entirely unaware of the manipulation, literally 'buying into an ideology that supports this structure' (i.e., capitalism and consumerism). The upper classes are born with the ability to recognize this but do nothing; few Alphas or Betas, aside from characters like Bernard, do much more than accept their roles. Indeed, the interactions among social classes, as will be discussed in more detail, are significant indicators of the perceived oppression by capitalism.

Relationships between different individuals do not exist in "Brave New World." The novel seems to refuse to differentiate the characters—they lack depth, even among the main characters. Perhaps Huxley suggests that the rise of technology and capitalism together deprives humans of their free will and expression. Love doesn’t exist, nor do the extremes of any emotion; instead, interactions remain superficial, depicted clearly through the males' remarks about women, primarily on their physical appearance (i.e., pneumatic quality), and the females' unabashed comments about their encounters. Moreover, the complacency of each social class with their status in the hierarchy indicates the socioeconomic effect of capitalism. Their absolute obedience to their role in the community reflects Marxist thoughts on the proletariat, who are falsely assured of their superiority over all else as long as they continue to consume, obey, and conform with their peers.

Almost four years ago, I took a course on Islam at CBC. One of the main subjects of heated debate in the class was whether Islam is a hostile religion. I feel that this question is more relevant today than ever. Reflecting on the events since 9/11, I've observed the mass media shift from a hostile view of Islam and extremists to an extreme tolerance of Islam in America. Back in 2001, I doubt we could have had a presidential candidate named Borac Obama, with apparent Muslim roots in his family.

The biography of the Prophet intrigues me because, from what I know of Muhammad's history, it contradicts his character. Based on what I previously knew and learned, I thought Muhammad forced people to convert to Islam. He would conquer tribes and compel them to adopt the Islamic faith. However, according to the biography, Muhammad is portrayed as a sort of martyr, misunderstood and even humbling himself before others. Subsequently, people gradually came to see the 'truth' in his teachings and sought him out.

There are also some striking similarities between the ministries of Jesus and the 'miracles' of Muhammad. The most obvious is when he multiplied mutton and milk so that there was more than enough for forty men. This style of writing makes me believe the authors wanted Muhammad to be seen as the humble prophet who did not need to prove anything but simply lived in truth and miracles. This kind of fallacy is the worst because it diminishes the miracles and life of Jesus Christ. To me, it's like they are trying to claim the life and personhood of Jesus through Muhammad.

Additionally, there are many stories in the biography that seem to suggest part of their agenda is to provide proof of 'witnesses' or how people 'on their own' converted to Islam. The issue, however, is that many stories are from at least a third-party perspective. The author illustrates in the story that he heard from someone who heard from someone else, and so on. I didn't appreciate this much because, despite their intention to prove the truth of the stories, I thought it weakened them and made them appear more suspicious.

What bothers me most about this work is that they attempt to exalt Muhammad as a godly man who was humble, endearing, wise, and gentle. But history contradicts the idea that Muhammad was a gentle and humble man, and I can't help but wonder if Muslims today know the true history behind Muhammad's rise to power.

The teachings of Jesus and the beliefs he held during his lifetime were quickly left behind as Christian thought evolved after his life. Looking at this history broadly, we see a trend of Christianity moving further away from its origins. Today's world seems to display a growing awareness and an unprecedented progressive tendency. While traditionalists remain and may resist any thinking beyond what they were taught, this segment of the population may not be influential enough to affect the whole. Among Christians, historical awareness will grow significantly in the coming years. A desire will spread to separate the doctrines added to Christianity over time from the true intent of its namesake. It may take decades or even centuries, but the outcome will be inevitable: a significant reversal in the trend of Christian history. There will be a return to its original form. A movement will grow that will strip away layers of doctrine, one by one, as if the clock were turning back, until only the conception of what Jesus introduced to humanity on behalf of God remains, before any other thinkers made such claims. When this trend spreads through the United States and Europe, influencing masses to worship as if we lived in the time of Jesus, following only his ideas, the church as an institution will remain strong to lead the way. However, as the theological clock moves backward, the extreme diversity within Christendom will reverse into more uniformity of belief and practice. Between regions, denominations, and divisions of all kinds, we will see increasing similarities instead of differences. Human history is full of great reversions. One example is how Christians were once persecuted, shunned, and killed by the Roman Empire, which later became a Christian institution. Our country has moved from African-American slavery to African-American leadership. The great reversion coming in our future will play out in the sphere of the Christian religion, undoing history in search of the source and unraveling diversity in the process. It is crucial to note that part of what will make this process possible is a method of reading Jesus' words as metaphorical rather than literal. So what has happened since Jesus' lifetime? If we look far enough back into history, we find only Judaism, the theological beginning of the Christian religion. Monotheism, the perception of a divinely revealed religion, and the authority of the Hebrew scriptures were all central to the religion by the time the Romans took control of Jerusalem in 63 B.C.E. The Jewish population did not share a single spirit. They were divided into Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, Zealots, and a majority of common people.

I believe that "The Jungle" illustrates how, deep inside, people are inherently greedy and self-centered. They want only to care for themselves and enhance their lives as much as possible, but they never look out for anyone beneath them. The Jungle depicts this in numerous ways. The most evident area is the owners and managers of the large factories. Their sole aim is to make their companies and factories as massive and impressive as possible. They are indifferent to anyone or anything that obstructs their path or gets harmed due to their progress. According to Upton Sinclair's work: "The line of the buildings stood clear and black against the sky; here and there, great chimneys rose from the mass, with the smoke stream reaching the end of the world." Sinclair endeavors to portray the significant damage this pollution causes. He shows that the owners disregard any person or animal that might be hurt. They are unconcerned with the vast smoke plumes rising from the factories or the runoff of animal waste from the thousands of pens in Packingtown. The owners and managers also showed no concern for the employees who enriched them. They would do anything to earn or save an extra dollar: "From top to bottom, the place is merely a boiling cauldron of jealousy and hatred; there is no loyalty or decency anywhere in it, and nowhere does a man matter against a dollar." They force their employees to endure awful hours, and without even a day's notice, they might lay off numerous people at once without compensation or assistance in finding a job. During the era in which "The Jungle" is set, there were few, if any, laws or regulations protecting workers' safety or well-being. This allowed managers and owners to act recklessly, pushing their employees to hasten progress and work in dreadful conditions. Although the book never states it directly, those who lived and worked themselves to death in Packingtown were simply expected to endure the terrible conditions both while working in the factories and living nearby. There were no agencies or organizations providing information or assistance to the workers. There were unions formed, but these often caused more harm than good as they profited from the poor workers. The workers were so poorly treated and had no means of escaping the Packingtown system that they were described as slaves: "Here is a population, low-class and mostly foreign, always on the brink of starvation and dependent on the whims of men just as brutal and unscrupulous as the old slave drivers; under such circumstances, immorality is just as inevitable and prevalent as it is under the system of chattel slavery."

Dream-Land is one of the poems Edgar Allan Poe considered among his better works. In "Dream-Land," Poe uses the term "Thule" in lines 6 and 56, which Mabbott traces back to Virgil. Virgil used the term to refer to an island north of Britain, which the Greeks saw as the edge of the known world. Though Virgil certainly used the term, there is a more recent source that deserves some credit. Poe was very interested in German authors. This quote is important because it highlights Poe's familiarity with Goethe's writings. Karl J. Arndt, in his book "Poe’s Politian and Goethe’s Mignon," comments on the similarity of their two poems and concludes that Poe was imitating Goethe. The Oxford Companion to English Literature states that Goethe was a celebrated writer of the poetic drama Faust, published in two parts, the first in 1808 and the second in the year of Goethe's death, 1832. Within the poetic verse of Faust's second part is a short poem titled "The King of Thule." The poem tells of a king whose wife dies after giving him a goblet. After her death, he begins to drink heavily and weep from the memory of his deceased queen. He then decides it is his time to die, giving his belongings to his children, except for the goblet. He walks to a cliff, throws the goblet into the ocean, closes his eyes, and dies. The nature of the King of Thule and the description of the king in Dream-Land are very similar, possibly a dark reflection of Poe’s loss and his reliance on drinking. In 1842, Faust was also adapted into a romantic drama by H. P. Grattan, less than a year before Poe used the term Thule in "The Pit and the Pendulum." Poe references Thule twice in his collected writings. Once he refers to "ultima Thule" in The Pit and the Pendulum, but he uses this phrase twice in "Dream-Land," framing the poem. "The King of Thule" and "Dream-Land" can be read as companion pieces. In "Dream-Land," the speaker describes the landscape of Thule as dark and lonely, haunted by dead friends, and perceives a shaded world without color. All these scenes would be reflected in "The King of Thule" by Goethe, as he has just lost his wife, feels lonely, and has lost his will to rule or even live. The entire poem is depicted as if the speaker has stepped into Goethe's poem. Goethe was a significant author whom Poe would have known, if for no other reason than his respect for Tennyson. Poe expressed this sentiment when asked if he admired Tennyson. Besides the connection to Tennyson, Poe would have been exposed to Goethe’s work through the many reproductions that occurred after the original publication.

Under California law, a customer who was injured after slipping and falling on an applesauce spill in a grocery store might be awarded punitive damages by demonstrating that the store manager acted with malice, as he was informed twice about the spill and failed to have it cleaned for half an hour because he was having dinner. A judge is unlikely to summarily dismiss Jennifer Palmer's claim for punitive damages. To justify an award of punitive damages, a plaintiff must present evidence that the defendant's actions were carried out with a willful and conscious disregard for the probable harm that would result, as well as show that the conduct was despicable. Palmer could argue that Martin should have been aware of the probable harm of not cleaning a spill, as multiple D&D customers had been injured from slipping in the months before Palmer’s accident; and despite this knowledge, he still did not ensure the spill was cleaned. Palmer’s argument that Martin’s actions were despicable is less convincing but remains reasonable, given that six slip-and-fall incidents had occurred in 2009 and Martin still failed to take appropriate measures to maintain the safety of his store. On October 13, 2009, at 5:00 pm, Rich Wayne, an employee of D&D Markets, informed his manager, Paul Martin, about an applesauce spill in an aisle. Martin told Wayne he was on a dinner break and "didn't have time to deal with customer complaints." At 5:15 pm, another employee, Mary J. Haddigan, also notified Mr. Martin of the spill, and Martin responded in the same way. At 5:30 pm on the thirteenth, the plaintiff, Jennifer Palmer, slipped and fell on the spill and sustained a serious back injury. Prior to Palmer’s accident, five different slip-and-fall incidents had been reported at D&D’s in 2009. Palmer is now suing D&D for compensatory and punitive damages related to her injury, and we are considering whether to file a motion for partial summary judgment against the punitive damage claim. In California, a plaintiff can recover punitive damages for a breach of an obligation not arising out of a contract if the defendant acted with "oppression, fraud, or malice." Cal. Civ. Code, § 3294(a) (Lexis 2010). The statute defines malice as conduct intended to cause harm, or absent such intent, the conduct must be "despicable" and committed with "a willful and conscious disregard of the rights or safety of others." id. at § (c)(1). Courts have characterized conduct as malicious when it is committed with a conscious disregard of the plaintiff’s rights, where the defendant "was aware of the probable dangerous consequences of his conduct, and that he willfully and deliberately failed to avoid those consequences." Taylor v. Super. Ct. of Los Angeles Co., 598 P. 2d 853, 856 (Cal. 1979).

She had always felt like something was missing. It was a desire that refused to be fulfilled. It began when she was about 14 years old, just entering teenage life. And it was still there 3 years later, at the age of 17. By now, she realized she wanted someone rather than something. Yet, she had no interest in boys. Some had been attracted to her, making clumsy attempts to court the unapproachable, but no one appealed to her. She often questioned herself with this strange feeling, trying to figure out what could possibly cause such an odd thing to happen to a teenage girl. The few years of contemplation had brought forth theories, but nothing good enough to speculate on. So she continued living her life, constantly questioning her desires.

A day at home was usually peaceful. Her parents were good and calm people. They never argued with each other, and strangely enough, arguments with their daughter were very rare. The only thing they ever argued about was her asserting her independence and free personality. She was the daughter of a very calm couple, but she definitely countered their energies with her extensive and fun personality, which made her very likable, especially since she was a nice person.

Today, however, was not a calm day. As she walked from room to room, trying to find some new inspiration for herself, she heard a short scream from the kitchen, the sound of her mother's beautiful voice. She ran into the room, starting to panic while frantically asking, "Mom?! Mom, what's wrong?!" She saw her mother lying on the floor, seemingly in pain, as she kept saying "Ouch" in short breaths. The mother's daughter ran to her and placed a hand on her to offer help. "Ouch... sweetie, I... need you to take me to the hospital." The words were rushed and pressed, and her daughter could tell she was in immense pain. "Okay Mom, just tell me where I can pick you up." Her mother indicated with her hands, and at that moment, the house's hero was very grateful she had taken classes to strengthen herself. She carried her mother to the car, laid her down in the back seat, and drove off.

A visit to the hospital brought the smell of disinfectant and illness, tinged with fear. But she wasn't sensing that, as her mind was too occupied with helping her mother. She quickly carried the injured woman inside and began calling for help from the doctors. A few worried faces gathered, and someone quickly brought a rolling bed and laid her mother on it. They took her for immediate examination, and her daughter was left to sit in worry.

Her mother had fallen from a step stool while trying to grab a vase from the highest cabinet they had.

This study aimed to demonstrate that adherence to a "Mediterranean Diet" (Med diet), indicated by a high "alternate Mediterranean (aMed) diet score," is linked with a reduced risk of chronic heart disease (CHD), stroke, and stroke mortality. The aMed diet is a modified version of the Med diet and is characterized by higher consumption of plant foods, including plant proteins (excluding potatoes, but including fruits, nuts, whole grains, and legumes), monounsaturated fats (compared to saturated fats), and fish, with lower consumption of animal products and saturated fats. Moderate alcohol intake is permitted.

Previous prospective studies documented an inverse relationship between adherence to a Med diet and the risk of total and cardiovascular mortality. An intervention trial showed that the Med diet was more effective than a low-fat diet in promoting weight loss and lowering the ratio of total to HDL cholesterol in obese individuals. Earlier studies did not focus on stroke or stroke mortality.

This epidemiological study followed 74,886 women aged 38 to 63 years without a history of cardiovascular disease or diabetes, who are participants in the Nurses' Health Study, a cohort study of 121,700 female nurses in 11 US states. From 1984 to 2004, the authors calculated an aMed diet score six times from self-reported "food frequency questionnaires" (FFQs), designed to assess nutrient intake over the previous year. Over 95% of the nurses continued participating throughout the 20-year period. FFQs underwent validation studies. Reports of CHD, fatal CHD, and stroke were confirmed by reviewing medical or hospital records, autopsies, or death certificates. Where records were unavailable, cases were deemed "probable" and included, with about 17% of all strokes and 24% of nonfatal myocardial infarctions classified as such. Body mass index, smoking status, aspirin use, multivitamin intake, menopausal status, and use of postmenopausal hormones were calculated for each FFQ, and starting in 1986, leisure-time physical activity was assessed.

To reduce random variation for an individual and better represent long-term dietary intake, cumulative averages of the aMed score from the repeated FFQs were calculated (averaging scores from the two previous years). Adjustments were made for "confounders" by adjusting for age, smoking, BMI, menopausal status, postmenopausal hormone use, multivitamin intake, alcohol intake, physical activity, and aspirin use.

Cox proportional-hazard modeling was used to assess the association between an aMed score and the risk of CHD and stroke, using separate models for fatal and nonfatal CHD and stroke types.

Greater adherence to the Mediterranean diet, as indicated by a higher aMed diet score, was associated with a lower risk of CHD and stroke in women. During 20 years of follow-up, 2,391 cases of CHD, 1,763 cases of stroke, and 1,077 cardiovascular disease deaths (fatal CHD and strokes combined) were identified. Women in the highest aMed quintile had a lower risk for both CHD and stroke compared to those in the lowest quintile (relative risk [RR], 0.71).

Hitler is alive in Burma, the sign reads.

Ellen Page, the star of Juno, stands alone on a street corner holding a piece of cardboard above her head, the disturbing message written in Sharpie on her sign. Burma, also known as Myanmar, is a Southeast Asian country governed by a tyrannical military junta that came to power in 1962 through a coup d'état. In 2007, a series of street protests took place, the first public protests in a decade. Led by a large number of Burmese monks, these protests were dubbed "The Saffron Revolution," named after the color of the robes the monks wore. After the initial uprisings, the general public began to take an interest in the protests, and while the Burmese government initially reluctantly allowed the monks to engage in peaceful gatherings, the violence soon escalated into what some considered an all-out war between the monks and the military junta, with the military actively invading and ransacking monasteries across the country. Foreign journalists were rounded up and imprisoned on sight, with a Japanese photojournalist named Kenji Nagai killed on September 27, 2007, simply for being present at a street protest. While the official death toll stands at 13, Colonel Hla Win, who defected from the army a few days prior to the official report, is quoted as saying, "Many more people have been killed in recent days than you've heard about. The bodies could be counted in several thousand."

This is nothing new. While these are some of the latest examples of atrocities occurring in our world, a government's desire to suppress dissent and maintain complete control over its citizens has existed for as long as civilization itself. Early Roman emperors declared themselves chosen by the gods to have full executive rule over every aspect of their society. Japanese emperors are believed to actually be gods, sent to our world to lead their people to prosperity through the invention of Motorola cell phones and hara-kiri, and our current president, George W. Bush, has weekly conference calls with Ted Haggard, the leader of Stupid People Worldwide, a subsidiary group of the Republican Party.

Some of the most well-known examples of such actions include incidents like the June 4, 1989 protest at Tiananmen Square, where intellectuals, labor activists, and students gathered to protest the authoritarian rule of the government. The death toll in that particular case varies widely, with official reports from the Chinese government stating 200-300 dead, while reports from the Chinese Red Cross claim between 2,000-3,000 dead. Another is the Rwandan genocide of the 1990s, where Hutu militia groups, aided by the Rwandan government, began systematically killing all Tutsis as well as political moderates, regardless of their ethnic backgrounds. Hitler's 'Third Reich,' a period spanning several years and multiple countries where anyone of Jewish background was rounded up and killed, is another extreme example.

Duke Ellington's legacy in jazz is largely due to his longevity and his creative ability to shape his orchestra. His presence at the piano is subtle in many of the compositions chosen for this task, but as a composer, Ellington excelled at creating rich and complex pieces that showcased the band members' individual talents. Ellington crafted the framework in which a soloist could improvise freely, in addition to writing tightly orchestrated pieces and phrases that utilized the unique styles of band members to highlight musical ideas. In doing so, he also emphasized the tone of the orchestra more generally, creating coherent and original sounds to fit each piece. Ellington's mastery of the individual players' sounds and his ability to bring them together in a growing ensemble allowed him to write some of the most innovative and brilliant pieces in jazz history.

The Grove Music Dictionary, when discussing Ellington's sound and innovation, mentions Creole Love Call as an example of using the voice "as a jazz instrument" throughout his career. This is an early example of Ellington's use of voice to add texture and color without being limited by lyrics. Creole Love Call also demonstrates Ellington's ability to complement the style of his soloists, something evident throughout his career. This slow, deliberate twelve-bar blues piece contains six choruses, as follows:

Chorus 1: Call and response between voice and reeds, with the voice starting smooth and melodic, then transitioning to a rougher sound towards the end.  
Chorus 2: Muted trumpet solo elaborating on the basic melody and emphasizing several extended blue notes.  
Chorus 3: Sweeping clarinet solo in a high register, supported by a subtle syncopated piano phrase.  
Chorus 4: Full band echoes the first chorus with a call and response by the brass and reed sections.  
Chorus 5: The climactic chorus of the piece, as the reeds now begin the call and response in a high register, backed by syncopated stop-time from the brass and rhythm sections.  
Chorus 6: A return to the structure of the first chorus, with call and response between voice and reeds. In this chorus, the voice takes on the sound of the “growl” technique, soloing as an instrument.  
Tag: Brief tag with a vocal run and a dissonant novelty ending by a trombone.

Ellington's use of voice to add a dimension of tone color to this piece is an example of a stylistic trait that permeates his work. In Hot and Bothered, recorded a year later, Ellington combines his skill at tight orchestration with his ear for tone color. A call and response phrase between “Bubber” Miley on muted trumpet and Baby Cox’s scat singing uses the vocal elements of Miley’s playing and the instrumental aspects of Cox’s voice to create a rich and complementary sound. It Don’t Mean a Thing (If It Ain’t Got That Swing) extends these ideas, as Ellington uses Joe “Tricky Sam” Nanton, a mainstay in Ellington’s orchestra, to great effect in introducing the melody on muted trombone.

Why do organisms evolve the way they do? Are there limitations or constraints that influence the direction of evolutionary change? Although D’Arcy Thompson stated in 1917 that "even now the zoologist has scarcely begun to dream of defining even the simplest organic forms in mathematical language," this still holds true today. More recently, mathematical modeling has been applied to general aspects of mollusk skeletogenesis through both ontogeny and phylogeny (e.g., Raup and Stanley, 1981). Our study explores how mathematical modeling of ontogenetic and phylogenetic changes in Prunum, combined with experimental studies, can be used to elucidate the mechanisms involved in the direction and magnitude of evolutionary-developmental change. We used X-ray images of Prunum species to determine quantitative parameters that could be used to model hypothetical and actual skeletal morphologies. These parameters were input into the software program CerioShell (Stone, 1995). We modeled hypothetical shell morphologies that could help interpret the boundaries of possible morphological change in Prunum. These results are being combined with experimental and descriptive studies to better understand macroevolutionary events in this clade.

A shell can be thought of as a structure like a tube that travels over time through 360 degrees of space. These rotations or turns of a coiled shell are called whorls, which are considered to spiral around an imaginary central axis. This axis runs through the central column of the shell and is known as the columella. The speed at which the whorls enlarge can vary, and a continuous line separates each whorl, referred to as a suture. In most shells, the largest whorl is the last one (body whorl). The spire includes all whorls except the last. The apex is the tip of the spire, and the opposite end is called the base. The animal extends out of its shell through an opening called the aperture.

Shells can be viewed in apical, basal, apertural, and abapertural views. (The "usual" orientation of a shell is an apertural view, with the aperture facing the viewer and the apex pointing upward.)

A method for counting whorls is shown below. First, the shell should be viewed from the apical view and then determine where the first suture begins. A line can then be drawn dividing the shell into two parts. Whorls are counted from this line and estimated to a quarter of a whorl.

A shell can be seen as a series of apertures that travel through time and space as the animal builds its shell. It is possible to trace the path of the aperture via the coordinates of the center of each whorl's aperture as well as the horizontal and vertical radius of the aperture.

This trajectory can be graphically and mathematically represented. Once a mathematical formulation is made, it is possible to vary parameters and modify the mollusk's skeletogenesis.

The neonatal and infant mortality rates in Indonesia have remained largely unchanged over the past decade. While the country is progressing towards many Millennium Development Goals, such as water and sanitation, the advancements in child and maternal health are significantly behind the necessary improvements to meet the 2015 targets. Various reasons for these deficiencies will be discussed, emphasizing the need to reinforce the health system rather than just focusing on program-specific interventions.

Indonesia has improved in terms of births attended by skilled health workers, with 72% of births now meeting this criterion. Nevertheless, this figure includes traditional workers, like midwives, who cannot perform medical interventions during complicated pregnancies (hence the significant percentage of maternal deaths caused by hemorrhage). Thus, the improvements in this indicator can be misleading, and much work is still required. Furthermore, there has been a reduction in the percentage of diarrhea cases in children under five treated by health professionals. Despite incomplete data on postnatal care, it is clear this area also needs attention, with low rates nationwide.
