Palmer could argue that Martin should have been aware of the probable harm of not cleaning a spill, as multiple D&D customers had been injured from slipping in the months before Palmer’s accident; and despite this knowledge, he still did not ensure the spill was cleaned. Palmer’s argument that Martin’s actions were despicable is less convincing but remains reasonable, given that six slip-and-fall incidents had occurred in 2009 and Martin still failed to take appropriate measures to maintain the safety of his store. On October 13, 2009, at 5:00 pm, Rich Wayne, an employee of D&D Markets, informed his manager, Paul Martin, about an applesauce spill in an aisle. Martin told Wayne he was on a dinner break and "didn't have time to deal with customer complaints." At 5:15 pm, another employee, Mary J. Haddigan, also notified Mr. Martin of the spill, and Martin responded in the same way. At 5:30 pm on the thirteenth, the plaintiff, Jennifer Palmer, slipped and fell on the spill and sustained a serious back injury. Prior to Palmer’s accident, five different slip-and-fall incidents had been reported at D&D’s in 2009. Palmer is now suing D&D for compensatory and punitive damages related to her injury, and we are considering whether to file a motion for partial summary judgment against the punitive damage claim. In California, a plaintiff can recover punitive damages for a breach of an obligation not arising out of a contract if the defendant acted with "oppression, fraud, or malice." Cal. Civ. Code, § 3294(a) (Lexis 2010). The statute defines malice as conduct intended to cause harm, or absent such intent, the conduct must be "despicable" and committed with "a willful and conscious disregard of the rights or safety of others." id. at § (c)(1). Courts have characterized conduct as malicious when it is committed with a conscious disregard of the plaintiff’s rights, where the defendant "was aware of the probable dangerous consequences of his conduct, and that he willfully and deliberately failed to avoid those consequences." Taylor v. Super. Ct. of Los Angeles Co., 598 P. 2d 853, 856 (Cal. 1979).

She had always felt like something was missing. It was a desire that refused to be fulfilled. It began when she was about 14 years old, just entering teenage life. And it was still there 3 years later, at the age of 17. By now, she realized she wanted someone rather than something. Yet, she had no interest in boys. Some had been attracted to her, making clumsy attempts to court the unapproachable, but no one appealed to her. She often questioned herself with this strange feeling, trying to figure out what could possibly cause such an odd thing to happen to a teenage girl. The few years of contemplation had brought forth theories, but nothing good enough to speculate on. So she continued living her life, constantly questioning her desires.

A day at home was usually peaceful. Her parents were good and calm people. They never argued with each other, and strangely enough, arguments with their daughter were very rare. The only thing they ever argued about was her asserting her independence and free personality. She was the daughter of a very calm couple, but she definitely countered their energies with her extensive and fun personality, which made her very likable, especially since she was a nice person.

Today, however, was not a calm day. As she walked from room to room, trying to find some new inspiration for herself, she heard a short scream from the kitchen, the sound of her mother's beautiful voice. She ran into the room, starting to panic while frantically asking, "Mom?! Mom, what's wrong?!" She saw her mother lying on the floor, seemingly in pain, as she kept saying "Ouch" in short breaths. The mother's daughter ran to her and placed a hand on her to offer help. "Ouch... sweetie, I... need you to take me to the hospital." The words were rushed and pressed, and her daughter could tell she was in immense pain. "Okay Mom, just tell me where I can pick you up." Her mother indicated with her hands, and at that moment, the house's hero was very grateful she had taken classes to strengthen herself. She carried her mother to the car, laid her down in the back seat, and drove off.

A visit to the hospital brought the smell of disinfectant and illness, tinged with fear. But she wasn't sensing that, as her mind was too occupied with helping her mother. She quickly carried the injured woman inside and began calling for help from the doctors. A few worried faces gathered, and someone quickly brought a rolling bed and laid her mother on it. They took her for immediate examination, and her daughter was left to sit in worry.

Her mother had fallen from a step stool while trying to grab a vase from the highest cabinet they had.

This study aimed to demonstrate that adherence to a "Mediterranean Diet" (Med diet), indicated by a high "alternate Mediterranean (aMed) diet score," is linked with a reduced risk of chronic heart disease (CHD), stroke, and stroke mortality. The aMed diet is a modified version of the Med diet and is characterized by higher consumption of plant foods, including plant proteins (excluding potatoes, but including fruits, nuts, whole grains, and legumes), monounsaturated fats (compared to saturated fats), and fish, with lower consumption of animal products and saturated fats. Moderate alcohol intake is permitted.

Previous prospective studies documented an inverse relationship between adherence to a Med diet and the risk of total and cardiovascular mortality. An intervention trial showed that the Med diet was more effective than a low-fat diet in promoting weight loss and lowering the ratio of total to HDL cholesterol in obese individuals. Earlier studies did not focus on stroke or stroke mortality.

This epidemiological study followed 74,886 women aged 38 to 63 years without a history of cardiovascular disease or diabetes, who are participants in the Nurses' Health Study, a cohort study of 121,700 female nurses in 11 US states. From 1984 to 2004, the authors calculated an aMed diet score six times from self-reported "food frequency questionnaires" (FFQs), designed to assess nutrient intake over the previous year. Over 95% of the nurses continued participating throughout the 20-year period. FFQs underwent validation studies. Reports of CHD, fatal CHD, and stroke were confirmed by reviewing medical or hospital records, autopsies, or death certificates. Where records were unavailable, cases were deemed "probable" and included, with about 17% of all strokes and 24% of nonfatal myocardial infarctions classified as such. Body mass index, smoking status, aspirin use, multivitamin intake, menopausal status, and use of postmenopausal hormones were calculated for each FFQ, and starting in 1986, leisure-time physical activity was assessed.

To reduce random variation for an individual and better represent long-term dietary intake, cumulative averages of the aMed score from the repeated FFQs were calculated (averaging scores from the two previous years). Adjustments were made for "confounders" by adjusting for age, smoking, BMI, menopausal status, postmenopausal hormone use, multivitamin intake, alcohol intake, physical activity, and aspirin use.

Cox proportional-hazard modeling was used to assess the association between an aMed score and the risk of CHD and stroke, using separate models for fatal and nonfatal CHD and stroke types.

Greater adherence to the Mediterranean diet, as indicated by a higher aMed diet score, was associated with a lower risk of CHD and stroke in women. During 20 years of follow-up, 2,391 cases of CHD, 1,763 cases of stroke, and 1,077 cardiovascular disease deaths (fatal CHD and strokes combined) were identified. Women in the highest aMed quintile had a lower risk for both CHD and stroke compared to those in the lowest quintile (relative risk [RR], 0.71).

Hitler is alive in Burma, the sign reads.

Ellen Page, the star of Juno, stands alone on a street corner holding a piece of cardboard above her head, the disturbing message written in Sharpie on her sign. Burma, also known as Myanmar, is a Southeast Asian country governed by a tyrannical military junta that came to power in 1962 through a coup d'état. In 2007, a series of street protests took place, the first public protests in a decade. Led by a large number of Burmese monks, these protests were dubbed "The Saffron Revolution," named after the color of the robes the monks wore. After the initial uprisings, the general public began to take an interest in the protests, and while the Burmese government initially reluctantly allowed the monks to engage in peaceful gatherings, the violence soon escalated into what some considered an all-out war between the monks and the military junta, with the military actively invading and ransacking monasteries across the country. Foreign journalists were rounded up and imprisoned on sight, with a Japanese photojournalist named Kenji Nagai killed on September 27, 2007, simply for being present at a street protest. While the official death toll stands at 13, Colonel Hla Win, who defected from the army a few days prior to the official report, is quoted as saying, "Many more people have been killed in recent days than you've heard about. The bodies could be counted in several thousand."

This is nothing new. While these are some of the latest examples of atrocities occurring in our world, a government's desire to suppress dissent and maintain complete control over its citizens has existed for as long as civilization itself. Early Roman emperors declared themselves chosen by the gods to have full executive rule over every aspect of their society. Japanese emperors are believed to actually be gods, sent to our world to lead their people to prosperity through the invention of Motorola cell phones and hara-kiri, and our current president, George W. Bush, has weekly conference calls with Ted Haggard, the leader of Stupid People Worldwide, a subsidiary group of the Republican Party.

Some of the most well-known examples of such actions include incidents like the June 4, 1989 protest at Tiananmen Square, where intellectuals, labor activists, and students gathered to protest the authoritarian rule of the government. The death toll in that particular case varies widely, with official reports from the Chinese government stating 200-300 dead, while reports from the Chinese Red Cross claim between 2,000-3,000 dead. Another is the Rwandan genocide of the 1990s, where Hutu militia groups, aided by the Rwandan government, began systematically killing all Tutsis as well as political moderates, regardless of their ethnic backgrounds. Hitler's 'Third Reich,' a period spanning several years and multiple countries where anyone of Jewish background was rounded up and killed, is another extreme example.

Duke Ellington's legacy in jazz is largely due to his longevity and his creative ability to shape his orchestra. His presence at the piano is subtle in many of the compositions chosen for this task, but as a composer, Ellington excelled at creating rich and complex pieces that showcased the band members' individual talents. Ellington crafted the framework in which a soloist could improvise freely, in addition to writing tightly orchestrated pieces and phrases that utilized the unique styles of band members to highlight musical ideas. In doing so, he also emphasized the tone of the orchestra more generally, creating coherent and original sounds to fit each piece. Ellington's mastery of the individual players' sounds and his ability to bring them together in a growing ensemble allowed him to write some of the most innovative and brilliant pieces in jazz history.

The Grove Music Dictionary, when discussing Ellington's sound and innovation, mentions Creole Love Call as an example of using the voice "as a jazz instrument" throughout his career. This is an early example of Ellington's use of voice to add texture and color without being limited by lyrics. Creole Love Call also demonstrates Ellington's ability to complement the style of his soloists, something evident throughout his career. This slow, deliberate twelve-bar blues piece contains six choruses, as follows:

Chorus 1: Call and response between voice and reeds, with the voice starting smooth and melodic, then transitioning to a rougher sound towards the end.  
Chorus 2: Muted trumpet solo elaborating on the basic melody and emphasizing several extended blue notes.  
Chorus 3: Sweeping clarinet solo in a high register, supported by a subtle syncopated piano phrase.  
Chorus 4: Full band echoes the first chorus with a call and response by the brass and reed sections.  
Chorus 5: The climactic chorus of the piece, as the reeds now begin the call and response in a high register, backed by syncopated stop-time from the brass and rhythm sections.  
Chorus 6: A return to the structure of the first chorus, with call and response between voice and reeds. In this chorus, the voice takes on the sound of the “growl” technique, soloing as an instrument.  
Tag: Brief tag with a vocal run and a dissonant novelty ending by a trombone.

Ellington's use of voice to add a dimension of tone color to this piece is an example of a stylistic trait that permeates his work. In Hot and Bothered, recorded a year later, Ellington combines his skill at tight orchestration with his ear for tone color. A call and response phrase between “Bubber” Miley on muted trumpet and Baby Cox’s scat singing uses the vocal elements of Miley’s playing and the instrumental aspects of Cox’s voice to create a rich and complementary sound. It Don’t Mean a Thing (If It Ain’t Got That Swing) extends these ideas, as Ellington uses Joe “Tricky Sam” Nanton, a mainstay in Ellington’s orchestra, to great effect in introducing the melody on muted trombone.

Why do organisms evolve the way they do? Are there limitations or constraints that influence the direction of evolutionary change? Although D’Arcy Thompson stated in 1917 that "even now the zoologist has scarcely begun to dream of defining even the simplest organic forms in mathematical language," this still holds true today. More recently, mathematical modeling has been applied to general aspects of mollusk skeletogenesis through both ontogeny and phylogeny (e.g., Raup and Stanley, 1981). Our study explores how mathematical modeling of ontogenetic and phylogenetic changes in Prunum, combined with experimental studies, can be used to elucidate the mechanisms involved in the direction and magnitude of evolutionary-developmental change. We used X-ray images of Prunum species to determine quantitative parameters that could be used to model hypothetical and actual skeletal morphologies. These parameters were input into the software program CerioShell (Stone, 1995). We modeled hypothetical shell morphologies that could help interpret the boundaries of possible morphological change in Prunum. These results are being combined with experimental and descriptive studies to better understand macroevolutionary events in this clade.

A shell can be thought of as a structure like a tube that travels over time through 360 degrees of space. These rotations or turns of a coiled shell are called whorls, which are considered to spiral around an imaginary central axis. This axis runs through the central column of the shell and is known as the columella. The speed at which the whorls enlarge can vary, and a continuous line separates each whorl, referred to as a suture. In most shells, the largest whorl is the last one (body whorl). The spire includes all whorls except the last. The apex is the tip of the spire, and the opposite end is called the base. The animal extends out of its shell through an opening called the aperture.

Shells can be viewed in apical, basal, apertural, and abapertural views. (The "usual" orientation of a shell is an apertural view, with the aperture facing the viewer and the apex pointing upward.)

A method for counting whorls is shown below. First, the shell should be viewed from the apical view and then determine where the first suture begins. A line can then be drawn dividing the shell into two parts. Whorls are counted from this line and estimated to a quarter of a whorl.

A shell can be seen as a series of apertures that travel through time and space as the animal builds its shell. It is possible to trace the path of the aperture via the coordinates of the center of each whorl's aperture as well as the horizontal and vertical radius of the aperture.

This trajectory can be graphically and mathematically represented. Once a mathematical formulation is made, it is possible to vary parameters and modify the mollusk's skeletogenesis.

The neonatal and infant mortality rates in Indonesia have remained largely unchanged over the past decade. While the country is progressing towards many Millennium Development Goals, such as water and sanitation, the advancements in child and maternal health are significantly behind the necessary improvements to meet the 2015 targets. Various reasons for these deficiencies will be discussed, emphasizing the need to reinforce the health system rather than just focusing on program-specific interventions.

Indonesia has improved in terms of births attended by skilled health workers, with 72% of births now meeting this criterion. Nevertheless, this figure includes traditional workers, like midwives, who cannot perform medical interventions during complicated pregnancies (hence the significant percentage of maternal deaths caused by hemorrhage). Thus, the improvements in this indicator can be misleading, and much work is still required. Furthermore, there has been a reduction in the percentage of diarrhea cases in children under five treated by health professionals. Despite incomplete data on postnatal care, it is clear this area also needs attention, with low rates nationwide.

Cesarean-section rates remain lower than expected at around 4%. These rates highlight another concerning issue. The cesarean rate is 7% in urban areas but only 2% in rural ones, pointing to unequal coverage nationwide. Access to healthcare services is mainly focused on urban areas. Another access issue involves vertical equity, with a 27% gap in service use between the poorest and richest quintiles, suggesting the poor have more difficulty accessing healthcare, likely due to out-of-pocket costs.

In considering steps to improve neonatal and maternal care indicators, the crucial question is how best to tackle the lack of service. Should Indonesia focus on program-specific strategies or strengthen the overall health system without concentrating solely on pre and post-pregnancy care? Programmatic approaches are attractive as they offer targeted, manageable objectives and generally yield quicker results. Yet, there are drawbacks. Heavy investment in one health sector area often means other areas lack funding, and human resources may move towards better-funded sectors (for example, the effect of international funding for HIV/AIDS on family planning). Additionally, running multiple parallel programs can result in service duplication and a lack of coordination, increasing paperwork and administrative tasks for supplies and funding.

The classification of popular music has expanded so much over the past 100 years that it is difficult to list them all definitively. Complicating matters, most, if not all, genres—rap, rock, country, jazz, folk, to name a few—have spawned multiple sub and sub-sub genres within their domain. Arguably, the sub-genre of heavy metal rock has become one of the most diverse and expressive genres of all popular music over the past 40 years. It is expressive because it displays a wide range of emotions, although they tend to lean toward the darker side of the spectrum. It is diverse in that quite soon after the genre's beginnings, people realized its real flexibility and started to take advantage of it to create their own sub-genre, which was then followed by sub-sub-genres, and the chain continues to this day.

Today, we have reached a point in the heavy metal movement where there are so many niches of groups that it is hard to determine what exactly heavy metal is. It has grown to incorporate many themes from other genres, but like everything else, it originated from somewhere. To properly understand the metal music that exists everywhere today, one must first understand what the metal movement is and why it is a movement rather than just a genre.

Metal is, in many ways, a movement defined by darkness. Metal can be considered a "music of more"—more bass, more volume, more violence, more theatricality. Less primitivism, more skill; people in metal bands truly know how to play their instrument, and it shows in the music. Metal is also—although it may not be surprising—a movement heavily influenced by drugs. There was a psychedelic drug boom in the mid-70s that led to people becoming crazier, leading them to create crazy, otherworldly records, using drugs as a scapegoat for their creation. It possesses many dark, visceral qualities, which were very new to the music scene because a large amount of popular music had qualities that did not align with the darker side of the emotional spectrum. Also, later generations of metal have taken some of their influence from the dark, visceral qualities that were so present in the Romantic Era. Lyrics such as the following express the darkness that is such a staple of the movement: (Byrne)

These lyrics from Helter Skelter display the darker side of the Beatles. It exhibits an up and down, supposedly that of drugs. This song is considered by some to be one of the first heavy metal songs. It was a response to a Rolling Stones song that was also on the heavier, darker side. The Beatles wanted to prove that they could be just as heavy as the Stones, so they included that song on The White Album.

A few decades before the Surrealist artists started painting their dreamlike works, the artist Henri Rousseau was meticulously crafting his own dreams, both literally and figuratively. "The Dream," a painting from 1910 by the renowned Post-Impressionist artist, not only depicts a woman in awe of the wonders of the land she visits within a dream but also represents Rousseau's personal dreams and aspirations as a painter. From the beginning of his career, he aspired for recognition, acceptance, and praise from other artists and art enthusiasts and found himself facing a challenging internal dilemma to achieve this ambition. "The Dream" is the work of Henri Rousseau that best reflects his lifelong internal struggle: whether to conform to or mimic certain painting styles to be accepted by the critical art world he so admired, or to allow himself to be creatively independent and unique, forging his own path.

Before one can analyze "The Dream" from this perspective, it's essential to be somewhat familiar with Rousseau's biographical background. Henri Rousseau was born on May 21, 1844, in the town of Laval in northwest France. His father was a tinsmith and hardware dealer who "enjoyed bourgeois prosperity" (Shattuck 47). Growing up, Rousseau received no formal education in the arts; instead, he was employed until the age of forty working for France as a gabelou, an employee of the municipal toll service, although he was mistakenly given the nickname douanier, a customs inspector (Shattuck 46). The death of his first wife, Clémence, following the deaths of eight infant children, left Rousseau with only one child, a daughter named Julia, and immense grief (Shattuck 49). As a result, he sought refuge in a new life and pursued painting to find comfort and new beginnings. Unlike some of his contemporaries who sentimentalized and romanticized peasants in painting, he was fundamentally a folk painter with the hopes and dreams of the average member of his class.

Rousseau's obsession with being accepted by the art world is somewhat understandable when seen in context: as discussed, he was not only uneducated in the formal ways of painting and started his career at a much older age, but he was creating works at the same time as many other talented and better-known modern artists. Although he had been working for many years already, Rousseau only began to receive proper recognition for his art around the same time that Matisse had started to build a reputation as an artist. In the book "Modern French Painters," author Jan Gordon asserts that the two, while technically competitors in the art arena, differed not only in style and subject matter but also in their reasons for painting in the first place: "Matisse was a painter who conceived a terror of painting in a trite way, while Rousseau’s desire was to paint a picture so conventional that he would be admitted to the Artiste Français" (92).

Many great thinkers have suggested an intimate connection between ethics and aesthetics, truth and beauty. I believe there is a fundamental reason for this. As John Keats says in "Ode on a Grecian Urn": "Beauty is truth, truth beauty—that is all / Ye know on earth, and all ye need to know." Much of what we know in life is learned through education or experience. Yet, as Keats implies, we seem to appreciate ethics and aesthetics without being taught in the expected ways. Both ethics and aesthetics attempt to describe rather than prescribe. Our studies of morality and beauty are mostly attempts to explain why a piece of art or literature is beautiful, or why an action is moral, rather than a set of rules for judging or creating good art or moral behavior.

Moreover, criticism of art or morals can never fully capture the essence of what is good or beautiful. A discussion about the value of da Vinci's Mona Lisa may revolve around concepts like foreground, background, contrast, or cultural context, but ultimately, these do not explain why it is good art. Rather, when asked about a favorite work of art or literature, it is common to hear a phrase like "There's just something about it" before a more complex or critical explanation follows. I believe that both art and morals can never be entirely reduced to a description of their qualities. As Flannery O'Connor says, "A story is a way to say something that can't be said any other way... you tell a story because a statement would be inadequate." No matter how completely we describe the properties of a literary work, there remains something transcendent. I believe that ethics shares this property. As Wittgenstein says, "It is clear that ethics cannot be expressed. / Ethics is transcendental." I propose that this "something," this je ne sais quoi, is the most powerful attribute of art and morality, and that this transcendental nature of both ethics and aesthetics provides a connection point between them.

I believe that morality and art are so closely related because we experience both most powerfully at a noumenal level, to use a Kantian term. They impact us in a way that can be felt but not fully explained. This link is even stronger when it comes to the art of literature. As McKean says, "What most distinguishes literature from other arts, what is, in truth, unique about the art, is its moral quality. It may be that moral standards are inappropriate to other arts, like music, but they seem to be as relevant to literature as they are to life itself. Living necessarily involves values... Literature is important to us precisely because of the values we find there."

Today's Germany is seen as a powerful and united nation, with a unique blend of culture spanning from the shadows of the Alps in Munich to the city of Kiel on the Baltic Sea. This culture is also evident from Cologne on the Rhine through the heart of Germany to the Saxon city of Dresden on the Elbe. With such a distinct culture, it is not surprising that the Germany we know today originates from several different sources and tribes.

Germania is the ancestral homeland of the Germans, and the origins of the name are hotly debated among scholars and historians. Tacitus claimed the name came from a Germanic tribe known as the Tungrians, who were previously known as Germans before crossing the Rhine to fight the Gaulish forces (Tacitus, 98). Julius Caesar first used the word "Germanus" in his commentary on the Gallic Wars, where he subdued the Gauls and battled with Germanic tribes that often crossed the Rhine under questionable pretenses. He borrowed this term from the Gauls themselves to distinguish between those he had conquered (the Gauls) and those he had not. While the origin remains uncertain, some suggest it referred to a neighbor in the Gaulish language. In the first chapter of his book on these wars, Julius Caesar wrote: "Germans, who dwell beyond the Rhine, with whom they (the Gauls) are continually waging war.....They contend with the Germans in almost daily battles." (Julius Caesar, 50-40 BC) Others propose the meaning comes from the spear used in warfare called a ger (O.E.D, 2010), or perhaps from the Old Irish word garim meaning "to shout," indicating the Germans were loud or noisy. (Names of Germany)

The early Roman historian Tacitus recorded in his AD 98 work "De Origine et situ Germanorum," which told of the origins of the Germans, that “I should regard (the Germans) as aboriginal, and not mixed at all with other races through immigration or intercourse. For, in former times it was not by land but on shipboard that those who sought to emigrate would arrive.......Who would leave Asia, or Africa, for Italy for Germany, with its wild country, its inclement skies, its sullen manners and aspect, unless indeed it were his home?” (Tacitus, 98)

Who would leave Rome for Germania? Certainly not the Romans, at least not yet. They would send expeditions into the lands of Germania for goods and occasionally lead land campaigns, but ultimately they mostly returned to their expansive empire. Thus, as Germanic tribes began to appear in the mid-first century, they lived at the borders of the Roman Empire, trading goods taken from the land and their skills by serving in the Roman army (Ozment, 2005, pg. 17).

The play "Twelfth Night" seems to suggest that while disguise is indeed useful in maintaining long-term deception, ultimately a person must reject this newly formed guise or risk losing themselves permanently in the process. A major issue with ending a deception, however, is that one might feel alienated in the process. Therefore, in the end, one has to choose between self-preservation and maintaining relationships with those around them. For although some may react neutrally upon discovering they've been deceived, others will not take the deception lightly and might feel offended by the entire charade.

The topic of deception in gender role reversal is particularly problematic because it raises many side issues, perhaps the most important being: why? Why does the individual feel the need to abandon their own identity and adopt a disguise in the form of the opposite gender? In Viola's case, it is clearly a form of self-protection: "I'll bring you to a captain in this town/ Where lie my maiden weeds, by whose gentle help/ I was preserved to serve this noble count..." (5.1.247-249)

Having newly arrived in a foreign land, Viola finds it necessary to pretend to be a man to protect herself from potential attackers. Viola's plan works but it also alienates her from the women around her, cutting her off from an important support system. To make matters worse, she is apparently so convincing as a man that Olivia confuses her with Sebastian and falls in love with her. "Whither, my lord? Cesario, husband, stay." (5.1.138) Additionally, she has to deal with suppressed romantic feelings between her and Orsino: "Boy, thou hast said to me a thousand times/ Thou never shouldst love woman like to me." (5.1.260-261)

Although this might be a somewhat progressive attitude, to the modern reader, "Twelfth Night" might be seen as illustrating how deception can facilitate the revelation of suppressed emotions, especially in the cases of Olivia and Orsino. Certain passages seem to suggest that the aforementioned characters may have unexpressed subconscious desires that the appearance of Viola/Cesario forces them to confront. For instance, is Olivia attracted to Cesario because Cesario appears as a man, or does Olivia secretly harbor feelings for women? One could argue that this is probably not the case, as Shakespeare's character Olivia seems more likely to parody those people of his time who judge others solely by their looks.

This is evidenced by the ease with which Olivia shifts her romantic interests from Cesario to Sebastian and begins to regard Cesario/Viola as family rather than a love interest: "A sister, you are she." (5.1.315)

German colonial rule was noted for its brutality by various observers, especially in relation to the genocide of the Ovaherero and Nama in German South West Africa. However, an entire colonial empire cannot be captured by such a simple description. The German colonial empire was as diverse in its policies and governing style as it was in its geography. Educational provision across the colonies was similarly varied. When the British took over German East Africa (Tanganyika) in 1919, they discovered a large population of educated and literate Africans. German educational efforts in Cameroon and other colonies were also praised by contemporary authors. The situation in South West Africa (present-day Namibia) was a stark contrast. Unlike in East Africa, where the government established state schools and played a significant role in educating the natives, in South West Africa, the task of native education was almost entirely left to missionary societies with limited government support. However, the government did invest significant resources in the education of Europeans in the colony, establishing a system of state schools and providing more substantial support and regulation for missionary schools. These educational policies had long-lasting effects on South West Africa, even after German rule. While other German colonies had significant numbers of literate and educated Africans, in South West Africa, "the overwhelming majority of the population remained untouched, uneducated, and illiterate." Various social, political, and economic factors led to the divergent experience of South West Africa. This paper aims to broaden the discussion by identifying these factors and paying particular attention to new research on the attitudes of settlers and colonial authorities towards native Africans. There is a wealth of literature specifically dealing with education in the German colonial empire. Most of these sources are in German and were written in the early twentieth century, during or shortly after the period of German colonial rule. The aim of early works was primarily to describe the features of educational systems in these colonies. Later writings in English expanded the discourse through comparative studies of education in the various German colonies and more detailed analyses of specific aspects of education. These studies highlighted significant differences in the educational systems of different colonies. The most prominent work explicitly addressing the topic of this paper is Cohen’s study of education in South West Africa and East Africa. Cohen compares the educational systems of the two colonies and discusses the factors that account for the differences between them. According to Cohen, the large settler population of South West Africa explains many of the distinguishing aspects of the colony’s educational system. Compared to Germany’s other colonial possessions, South West Africa had a moderately temperate climate, although much of the territory is covered by arid desert. The European population of South West Africa reflected the relatively hospitable conditions. By 1913, nearly 15,000 whites lived in South West Africa, whereas only 5,336 lived in the colony with the next largest settler population, East Africa.

The United States of America and Mexico serve as an example of two nations that were once plagued by a long-standing rivalry, lasting 57 years from 1836 to 1893 (Diehl and Goerts 2000, p. 145). The pinnacle of this rivalry was the Mexican-American War of 1846-1848, during which the United States attacked and defeated Mexico, securing Texas and the American Southwest as new territories. Many other conflicts occurred between the two nations, eventually subsiding just before World War I. The rivalry originated from clashes over key issues such as religion, culture, and tradition, as well as significant material interests (Schmitt 1974, p. 30-31).

This situation is similar to many other nations with enduring rivalries with neighbors. Countries that share a border often experience conflicts of interest, leading to rival positions between them. The United States and Mexico are not unlike other persistent rivalries between bordering nations. David M. Pletcher (1977) notes that "only in Mexico and Cuba can one find long-lasting overarching American diplomatic problems" (p. 41). Indeed, both of these countries are geographically close to the United States and have been its rivals, while other Latin American nations have enjoyed good relations with the United States.

Religious issues created a rift between the two nations, a problem that has troubled many throughout history. Sally Frahm (2001) states that "if in the twentieth century Americans opposed fascism and communism, in the eighteenth and nineteenth they opposed Catholicism and monarchy" (p. 86). Much like the Cold War rivalry between the United States and the Soviet Union, part of it was an ideological struggle and part a competition over interests deemed vital by each nation. However, in this case, the ideological struggles were based not on political structures but on religious preferences of the United States and Mexico. This distrust stemmed from the historical distrust between the English and Spanish. Inheriting these feelings of distrust from their former colonial rulers was a major obstacle in establishing amicable foreign relations between the United States and Mexico.

Diehl and Goerts (2000) identify 17 disputes between Mexico and the United States during the 57-year rivalry. Most of the disputes described by Diehl and Goerts during this period were territorial issues related to border raids from Mexican territory into Mexico and other frontier problems. Border raids by bandits and outlaws into American border towns were a significant problem until both the United States and Mexico exerted military force at their borders (Schmitt 1974, p. 97).

Schmitt (1974) explains that the rivalry between the two nations began to diminish as "Mexico became clearly dependent on the United States in a substantial way" (p. 109) and eventually ended as American ambitions "shifted from territorial expansion to economic intervention in Mexico" (p. 110) in the latter part of the 19th century.

Fifteen years ago, I was suddenly and unexpectedly disabled by an illness I never knew existed.

At that time, I was a nurse. I chose my profession driven by a deep-seated need for the safety and security I lacked as a child. "You'll always be able to find work; people will always get sick," was the mantra I heard repeatedly as I reached adolescence and beyond. So, even though my dream was to become a scientist or a journalist—preferably a bit of both—I chose nursing.

Yet, there I was: 46 years old, single, no money in the bank, and unable to work. To this day, I am disabled, and after 15 years of living on Social Security Disability, I literally have nothing left that I can call "mine." I manage to get by, but every day is a struggle and a challenge to my security, safety, and self-esteem. Nothing in my life is certain anymore; still, there is one thing I know to be true. I could not have made it through all these years without the help of my family and a few good friends, no matter how strong I was. And believe me, when real disaster strikes, you don't feel strong at all.

My point is that there will always be emergencies in life—big and small. There are no guarantees, and no matter how well one prepares, some things are simply too big to overcome on your own.

I fully agree that in the U.S., we need to stop putting all our faith in big government; it's moldy and falling apart anyway. But I would much prefer to see Americans learning to trust each other again—learning to help one another and to ask for help—rather than having each of us individually rushing to the backyard to build fallout shelters.

The Conservatives in the U.S. speak of the "rugged individualism" that built this country; but in truth, what sustained our forefathers in tough times wasn't rugged individualism, it was compassion, mutual respect, and the sharing of resources. The pioneers who crossed the Rockies in wagon trains did not make it to the coast by going it alone.

So, by all means, be prepared. I am. I have a disaster kit; first aid supplies, water purification tablets, plastic sheeting, and duct tape for the windows in case of a biological attack. I have several flashlights and all kinds of batteries, lots and lots of candles, waterproof matches, and canned goods, too. If you have the land and resources for a small farm and the ability to can or preserve your own food—do it. It's a great idea, as is a wood stove, as long as you don't live in an apartment.

But while you're at it, get to know your neighbors.

Sometime in the fifth or sixth century BCE, a prince was born who would later be known as Buddha. Throughout his life, he renounced the world and attained enlightenment, and his teachings led to the formation of Buddhism, with its most orthodox sect known as Theravada Buddhism. This religion is approximately two-and-a-half thousand years old; it appears different today than it did during Buddha's lifetime. This is evident everywhere, for example in the Theravada nation of Sri Lanka, where the annual water-cutting ceremony is held. Both monks and laypeople participate in this ceremony, and it holds some religious significance, despite the fact that Buddha never taught about such a festival. These differences range from superficial traditions to the soteriological core of the religion. The Theravada Buddhist community has had to adapt its doctrinal principles over time, from both the monastic and lay perspectives. This can be attributed to both external and internal forces, both hostile and benign.

There are several qualifying terms that will be frequently used in this discussion. There is the concept of internal versus external. Here, an internal force is defined as a force arising from members of the Buddhasasana, regardless of monastic status. An external force is any force coming from non-Buddhists. A hostile force is any force that harms or intends to harm the Buddhist community—a force stemming from a negative perception of Buddhism. A benign force is one that does not intend to harm or assist the Buddhist community—though it might end up doing one or the other as a side effect. These terms will appear repeatedly throughout this discussion.

First, it is important to explore the basics of the religion—the doctrines at the core of Theravada Buddhism. Buddhists seek refuge in the triple gem of the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma essentially consists of the Tripitaka—the three baskets—of Buddhist texts. The Sutta Pitaka contains all the Suttas, the Vinaya Pitaka contains the disciplinary rules, and the Abhidhamma Pitaka contains the metaphysical components of Buddhism. The metaphysical notions include concepts like Anatta—no soul, Dukkha—innate suffering in life, and Anicca—impermanence of everything. Only by understanding these concepts can one end Sansara, the cycle of death and rebirth, which occurs continuously. Along with Sansara, lobha—desire, dosa—hatred, and moha—delusion will end when one becomes enlightened. In the Vinaya Pitaka, rules for life are outlined. For laypeople, there are five precepts (I shall not kill, I shall not lie, I shall not steal, I shall not engage in sexual misconduct, and I shall not take intoxicating substances). For monks, there are many more disciplinary rules to follow. The most fundamental doctrinal concept in Buddhism is the notion of the four noble truths. First, Dukkha; the truth that life is suffering. Second, that attachment causes suffering. Third, that suffering can be overcome.
